gb.deck: A first-person shooter for the TurboGrafx-16 in which the player navigates the narrow corridors of a space station and eradicating hostile aliens.
A turn-based RPG featuring the famous fictional sailor Sinbad on another mysterious voyage.

A side-scrolling space shoot 'em up. The player is the only force capable of stopping a planet-devouring, bio-organic entity which is approaching the solar system. The most notable feature in the game is the fact that the player's ship is armed with adjustable armored jaws to defeat enemies.
A puzzle action game from French studio Loriciel featuring the titular fuzzball as he runs around painting his world pink. Would be followed by Super Skweek.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Game Gear, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, TurboGrafx-16

gb.deck: A vertical scrolling shoot 'em up for the TurboGrafx-16 from Hudson, Soldier Blade is part of the Star Soldier franchise.
gb.platforms: TurboGrafx-16, Wii Shop, PlayStation Network (PS3), PlayStation Network (PSP), Wii U

gb.deck: A wicked sorceress wants to take over the world via her 12 Zodiac minions. Can a pink slinky like character defeat them and foil her evil plans? This game was called "Mesopotamia" in Japan.
A volleyball game for the TurboGrafx-16. It depicts the court from the side, like most volleyball games, and adopts a caricature-based art style.
This platformer sequel to Son Son was only released on the PC Engine in Japan.

gb.aliases: 3D Space Harrier, Sega Ages Space Harrier
gb.deck: Play as a flying dude holding a large cannon as he takes on giant mechs, flying mushrooms, and fire-breathing dragon skeletons.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Game Gear, Sega Master System, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, ZX Spectrum, Nintendo Entertainment System, Sega 32X, Saturn, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, Wii Shop, PC, Sharp X68000, NEC PC-8801, Sharp X1, FM-7, NEC PC-6001, Nintendo 3DS eShop, Nintendo Switch

gb.deck: The first console-exclusive Space Invaders game, featuring classic and enhanced modes. Released exclusively in Japan for the PC Engine.
A falling blocks puzzle game for the PC Engine. By matching pairs of symbols with opposing designs, they will cancel each other out and remove similar symbols from the grid.
A space sim game that balances its time between adventure elements and a Z-axis shoot 'em up.
A video game adaptation of the famous strategic board game. Find the opponent's flag, and watch out for that spy.

gb.aliases: Street Fighter 2: Champion Edition, SF2CE, Street Fighter II': Special Champion Edition
gb.deck: The first update to the smash-hit fighting game Street Fighter II balances various aspects of the gameplay while adding support for playable bosses and mirror matches.
gb.platforms: Genesis, Sega Master System, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, Wii Shop, Sharp X68000

gb.deck: A simulation game in which the player modifies and upgrades their own mech fighter.
A train-based boardgame for the PC Engine, Famicom, and Game Boy.
gb.platforms: Game Boy, Nintendo Entertainment System, TurboGrafx-16

gb.deck: A Super iteration in the Momotarou Dentetsu series of railway-based board games released for the PC Engine, Super Famicom, and Game Boy.
gb.platforms: Game Boy, Super Nintendo Entertainment System, TurboGrafx-16

gb.deck: A vertical-scrolling shoot 'em up and part of the Star Soldier franchise.
gb.platforms: TurboGrafx-16, Wii Shop, PlayStation Network (PS3), PC, PlayStation Network (PSP), Wii U

gb.deck: A volleyball game for the TurboGrafx-16, Sega Genesis, and Arcade. Unlike many volleyball games of this era, which depicts the whole court, Super Volleyball is on a single 2D plane. It also has four people per team instead of two, as per standard volleyball rules.
A side-scrolling brawler for the Arcade and PC Engine featuring the titular Japanese Sengoku warlord. Not to be confused with the NES strategy game of the same name.
A TurboGrafx-16 and Genesis platformer based on the TaleSpin license. Unlike the Capcom NES/GB shoot 'em up, Baloo is on foot and looking for vital objects in distinct regions.
A side-scrolling platformer featuring a bizarre cast of characters created by manga artist Akira Miyashita.

igdb.name: Terra Cresta II: Mandler no Gyakushuu

gb.deck: The sequel to Nichibutsu's arcade shoot-'em-up, exclusively for the PC Engine.

A helicopter shoot-'em-up developed by Sega. The Arcade version made use of Sega's 3D super scaler technology to create city environments where the buildings would appear to have depth. The subsequent home versions sadly lacked this feature.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Genesis, Sega Master System, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, MSX, ZX Spectrum, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, PC, Sharp X68000, Nintendo 3DS eShop

gb.deck: An Arcade style side-scrolling beat 'em up with a Chinese Kung Fu setting. It was converted to European home computers and the TurboGrafx-16.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, ZX Spectrum, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade

gb.deck: A sci-fi themed pinball game on the TurboGrafx-16. The pinball can activate time machines which sends it to bonus tables in different time zones.
Timeball is a puzzle game for the TurboGrafx-16 that is a mix between sliding block puzzles and Pipe Dream. It is known as Blodia or Diablo in Japan.
A Breakout variant which allows for vertical movement around top-down environments. The goal is still to clear the stage of blocks by using the player's craft for angled shots.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, ZX Spectrum, Nintendo Entertainment System, TurboGrafx-16, PC

gb.deck: A scatological shoot 'em up released for the PC Engine in 1992. It was developed by Bits Laboratory and published by Media Rings.

Players climb the tower, defeat Druaga and rescue Princess Ki in this maze-style, action role-playing game. Originally released by Namco for arcades in 1984, its combination of hack & slash combat and RPG elements laid the foundations for the action RPG genre.
gb.platforms: Game Boy, MSX, Nintendo Entertainment System, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, Wii Shop, Nintendo 3DS eShop

gb.deck: A vertical shoot 'em up in which the player can switch between three flying kids with different weapons.
A puzzle game for the TurboGrafx-16. The goal is to push like objects together to make them disappear, like Puzznic. The game plays around with many protagonists and themes.
An enhanced re-release of the 1987 Tsuppari Oozumou game for Famicom.
An early shooter platformer originally developed for European home computers, best known for its heavy metal soundtrack by Chris Huelsbeck.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Game Boy, Genesis, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, ZX Spectrum, TurboGrafx-16, Commodore CDTV

gb.deck: A basketball game and part of Cinemaware's TV Sports series. The player can select one of eight fictional teams and take on their rivals on the court.
A football game and part of Cinemaware's TV Sports series of sports simulators. The game uses fictional teams like the Blizzards and the Rhinos.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Atari ST, Commodore 64, TurboGrafx-16, PC

gb.deck: A hockey game for the TurboGrafx-16 and part of Cinemaware's TV Sports series.
A sidescrolling mecha shoot 'em up for the TurboGrafx-16 and NEC PC-8801.
A racing game for the Turbografx-16 developed by Hudson. It uses the behind-the-car viewpoint popularized by Sega's OutRun.
gb.platforms: TurboGrafx-16, Wii Shop, PlayStation Network (PS3), PlayStation Network (PSP), Wii U

gb.deck: A beat 'em up where players control a martial artist, Thomas, who must rescue his girlfriend, Madonna. Released in 1988, this is the spiritual sequel to the first beat 'em up, Kung-Fu Master (Spartan X).
gb.platforms: Amiga, Sega Master System, Amstrad CPC, Atari ST, Commodore 64, MSX, ZX Spectrum, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, Wii Shop, Wii U

gb.aliases: QIX Neo, Ultimate QIX, The Jintori ~Volfied 1500
gb.deck: The third game in Taito's QIX series, Volfied loses the geometric abstraction of previous games in favor of a more sci-fi look.
gb.platforms: Amiga, Genesis, Atari ST, Commodore 64, PlayStation, TurboGrafx-16, Arcade, Wii Shop, PC

gb.deck: A Mahjong game from Video System for the PC Engine. Like many video game adaptations of the board game, it is one-on-one rather than four player.
A breeding/racing simulator developed by Tenky for the PC Engine.
A golf sim from Data East for the PC Engine. It later received a rerelease on the Wii Shop in Japan.
An action game presented as "hero show" developed by Namco.
A baseball simulator for the Turbografx-16, developed by Hudson. Originally released in Japan as Power League.
A multiplayer tennis game on the TurboGrafx-16. It is known as Pro Tennis: World Court in Japan. Perhaps most notable for its unusual "Quest Mode", which frames the game as a Dragon Quest clone.
An action horseracing game for the PC Engine. Part of Namco's "World" series of sports games.

A competitive sports game for the TurboGrafx-16, developed and published by Hudson. It features numerous sports that appear in the Olympics, such as track and field, archery, rowing and swimming. It is part of Hudson's larger Power Sports series, which also includes World Class Baseball.
gb.platforms: TurboGrafx-16, Wii Shop, PlayStation Network (PS3), PlayStation Network (PSP), Wii U

gb.deck: A vertically-scrolling shoot 'em up in the Xevious franchise. Adds bosses, power-ups and a story to the Xevious model.
A top-down action game for the TurboGrafx-16 featuring a skateboarding bear that has to defeat B-movie monsters to save his town. Its soundtrack features synthesized versions of hit Beach Boys songs.
The first game in a Japanese drag racing series that contains RPG elements.
A platformer/puzzle game based on a Japanese movie. It is heavily inspired by Tecmo's Solomon's Key.
